in pays attention to sound in both musical and nonmusical contexts, specifically the cacophony of British industrialization. Sound Authorities begins with the place of acoustics in early nineteenth-century London, examining scientific exhibitions, lectures, spectacles, workshops, laboratories, and showrooms. He goes on to explore how mathematicians mobilized sound in their understanding of natural laws and their vision of a harmonious ordered universe. In closing, Gillin delves into the era’s religious and metaphysical debates over the place of music (and humanity) in nature, the relationship between music and the divine, and the tensions between spiritualist understandings of sound and scientific ones.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMathematicszEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aMathematicszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aMusic and sciencexHistoryy19th century. 0aMusicxAcoustics and physicsxHistoryy19th century. 0aMusicxAcoustics and physicszEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aMusiczGreat Britainy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSound. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  ascience, music, Britain, acoustics, natural philosophy, sound, history, experiment, nineteenth century, epistemology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226809175423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226809175/original  a978-3-11-073